            </srcinfo>
            <srcinfo>
                <srccite>
                    <citeinfo>
                        <title>GISMGR.STREET_CENTERLINES</title>
                    </citeinfo>
                </srccite>
                <srcscale>7600</srcscale>
                <typesrc>onLine</typesrc>
                <srccitea>GISMGR.STREET_CENTERLINES</srccitea>
                <srccontr>Fairfax County street centerlines and some attributes including street name and address ranges</srccontr>
            </srcinfo>
            <procstep>
                <procdesc>Extract data from multi-modal transportation model to make a layer usable by the GIS community. The process involves joining multiple tables (centerlines, address ranges, street inventory) to house the attributes of the street centerlines that can be available for GIS use. This process will happen on a regular basis (daily or weekly) to have the most up to date street centerline information available to the GIS users as possible.</procdesc>
            </procstep>
            <procstep>
                <procdesc>All source data was provided to Spatial Systems Associates. The data was loaded into the transportation data model by matching existing attributes with new attributes within the model and making any changes to the values to fit into the domains. For geometry the data was edgematched at the boundary of each jurisdiction and Fairfax County. There were areas that needed to be adjusted because it did not match. The primary adjustments were made to the Fairfax County data trying to leave the VGIN RCL data as is as much as possible. Once the data was matched and seamless at the jurisdiction borders it was loaded into the data model. Geometry issues do remain in the VGIN RCL data that is not adjacent to the County jurisdictional boundary that has not been completely fixed. The fix for this is in discussion with VGIN and surrounding jurisdictions. For attributes, as many that could be mapped into the data model were loaded. The Fairfax County street names and address ranges were validated using the MAR point data. The Fairfax City and VGIN RCL data was not able to be validated due to lack of address points from those surrounding jurisdictions as well as time and manpower. The oneway attribute was reviewed and corrected on the major roads that go into and out of the County to allow for proper routing. Speed limits for segments outside of the County were originally coded as 33 mph but are now being reviewed on a segment by segment basis using various online sources to get a more accurate speed limit value on all segments throughout the region. Roadway names on major roads segments outside of the County were standardized so that they were consistent across the region (i.e. I66 and I95)</procdesc>
                <proccont>
